Endangered cute dog meets bullied cute boy and they take turns rescuing each other in a "comedy/adventure" flick designed to appeal to kids from 3 to 10. There are enough fart jokes and crotch hits to appeal to any red-blooded boy and enough sentimental dog-boy-girl moments to register with girls, but for a movie that relies on bad animatronic squirrels and groundhogs, not to mention wildly overplayed slapstick by the three bad guys (auditioning for a Three Stooges movie), this show runs on far too long and is far too padded to succeed as entertainment.

DOG GONE (2008) - PG  107 minutes

Dog Gone is basically, Home Alone in the woods. When 12 year old Owen rescues a dog from three men abusing the dog at a highway rest stop, he has no idea that the three are bumbling jewel thieves and that the dog is carrying five million dollars worth of stolen diamonds. Owen takes the dog back to his secret fort, high on a wooded ridge, a ridge that is also home to the Madman of the Mountain.  With a deadline approaching, the three jewel thieves search for Owen and finally grab him at his house. But Owen escapes back to his fort, which he has rigged with ingenious booby-traps and a wicked tennis-ball cannon named the Bully Buster.  The three dumb-as-rocks thieves, played with gusto by French Stewart, Kevin Farley and Kelly Perine, follow Owen to a final show-down.  After a hilarious battle, Owen and the dog, who Owen has named Diamond, are captured again. But Owen has unseen allies in two squirrels named Blabbermouth and Chatterbox and the mysterious, Madman on the Mountain.  In the end, the three jewel thieves wish theyd never been born. Dog Gone delivers all the hilarious and good-natured comedy that a classic family film should.

My 6 year old son loves this movie. It's is funny and sweet, a few lessons can be learned from the little boy who is in this movie. He is responsible by having a paper routt (spelling?) he is an inventor, he doesn't judge the wild man who lives in the woods, and most importantly in the movie he is helping save a dog from the bad guys. French stewart is in the movie, and plays a bad guy. If you liked him in third rock from the sun, you can watch him here too. It's a kid movie and I am glad to see a positive role model for little boys and girls, with out any added bad language and violence.

Although I readily admit that I have a penchant for films shot in my hometown and actually know some of the folks involved with the making of this movie. Since it only explains how I happened to purchase the DVD, this is a very wholesome family film that will appeal to most, if not all children and a significant portion of adults who have children. It's one of our six year old's favorite movies and she doesn't have any of the potential biases listed above. Nor does she enjoy anything other than animated features, so this was outside her comfort zone and a pleasant surprise for all. It's cute, funny and has a very uplifting message at the same time. You'll recognize a lot of faces in this one, including the talented Farley brothers.
